items.title: Agrotis spp.
items.content_text: Mobile phone photos of unidentified moth under the porch light near the front door.  I was moved to take the photos because moths are something of a rare event around the porch light these days.

items.title: Pimelea spinescens subsp. spinescens, Sciaridae spp.
items.content_text: A fuzzy photo taken by a colleague today with a point-and-shoot camera of a flowering male Pimelea spinescens plant at Mount Cottrell, with what appears to be a pollinator in action.  In another image the insect has its head inside the flower.  Pollinators for Critically Endangered Spiny Rice-flower are not yet known, so we'd love to know what this creature is, at least to family if possible.

items.title: Cervus unicolor
items.content_text: Roadkill adult female Sambar Deer on the city bound side of the Calder Freeway about 200m north of the Black Forest Drive overpass.

items.title: Ulmus X hollandica, Xanthogaleruca luteola
items.content_text: This summer has seen a massive cohort or two of Xanthogaleruca luteola, and most elms in the town have been seriously defoliated (except for some of the variegated cultivars).  Some nights there are thousands of dead beetles piled up outside lit shop windows, and I've had a steady stream of them inside my house.

items.title: Austracantha minax, Pieris rapae rapae
items.content_text: Cabbage White butterfly trapped in dilapidated Jewel Spider web.

items.title: Xanthogaleruca luteola
items.content_text: There are lots of these in the house I've just moved into in the centre of Kyneton. I haven't seen any frass around the place to suggest that their larvae are eating the house, but they just keep appearing! About 5mm in length. Excuse the poor mobile phone image.

items.title: Senna form taxon 'filifolia'
items.content_text: Re-planted Senna along Little Blind Creek

items.title: Antechinus agilis
items.content_text: Adult male Antechinus agilis found recently drowned in the footwell of a paddle-o boat.  Very modified habitat; little undergrowth to speak of.  Apparently healthy looking individual otherwise.

items.title: Phascogale tapoatafa
items.content_text: Dead putrefied carcass found (by dog) in peppermint/candlebark grassy open-forest.  Identifiable, but otherwise too decomposed for a specimen collection.

items.title: Cervus elaphus
items.content_text: Female (hind) Reed Deer captured on trail cam. In private land next to Wombat State Forest at Spring Hill 3444.  Have seen up to 6 hinds at a time. None tagged or marked, living feral but possibly farm escapes originally.

items.title: Coprinus comatus
items.content_text: Shaggy capped white Agaracales sp with black gills. Growing in manicured couch lawn in suburban Melton.

items.title: Thysanotus tuberosus subsp. tuberosus
items.content_text: This species is coming towards the end of its flowering season at this site, but there are still a few around. I presume it's T. tuberosus, but I'm unsure.

items.title: Amanita spp.
items.content_text: Common in this forest over the last 4-6 weeks. With my limited fungi field skills I don't know what the species is. Looks close to Amanita ochrophylloides. Fruiting body c. 120mm diameter in this case, but many are larger.

items.title: Dipodium roseum s.s.
items.content_text: Lots of multi-stemmed plants this year.

items.title: Dipodium roseum s.s.
items.content_text: Despite the enormous flush of annual grasses this year after all the rain, this poor single Dipodium lives to fight another year - this time sending up 1.5 flower spikes. I haven't found any other specimens in this forest/woodland patch yet. It's survival prospects here are tenuous at best.

items.title: Litoria peronii
items.content_text: Two Peron's Tree-frogs calling at last light. I've not heard them here before over the last ~5 years.

items.title: Derwentia derwentiana
items.content_text: Several plants on the road cutting of Allens Creek Road, Blackwood North. I don't recognise the plant in question.

items.content_text: Recent site works at the quarry, the kangaroos spending more time in our yard! 7 individuals, various ages including with young in pouch.
